The secondary projectiles have been produced by the
fragmentation of a primary Ni-58 beam at 650 MeV/
nucleon impinding on a beryllium target,4 g/cm**2
By means of a Delta-E-B(P)-TOF measurement, the
fragments have been identified and their
charge-changing probabilities in targets of CH(2), C,
Al and Pb have been determined.
Between the two ionization chambers, a target ladder
with four different targets was installed. The target
thicknesses were 2.728 g/cm**2 for the CH(2) target,
2.323 g/cm**2 for the carbon target, 3.254 g/cm**2 for
the aluminum target and 5.466 g/cm**2 for the lead
target. These thicknesses yield a secondary-beam energy
of about 440 MeV/nucleon at the center of the targets.
The correction for background reactions was performed
by means of the target-out measurements.

The error bars of the experimental data are
mainly due to statistical uncertainties.  Systematic
errors arise from uncertainties concerning the target
thickness less 1% as well as from those interactions in
the detector materials which are not corrected for in
the target-out measurements.  However, the interaction
probabilities for these reactions which include mainly
neutron-loss channels in the detectors are very small.
The neutron-removal probability in the detector
material, which could lead to a wrong isotope
identification, is estimated to be less than 1%.
Charge- loss interactions in the scintillator or in the
entrance window of the ionization chamber move the
event out of the identification condition of the
Delta-E-TOF spectrum and thus eliminate these events.
Although being very small, these errors have been taken
into account when determining the uncertainties given
